<DOC><DOCNO> AP890729-0120 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1922EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Judiciary     07-29 0186</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Sudan-Judiciary,0193</SECOND><HEAD>Military Regime Gives Itself Broad Powers Over Judiciary</HEAD><DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The country's new military ruler furtherconsolidated power Saturday by decreeing broad judicial powers forhimself.   The order gives Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan el-Bashir power to appointthe chief justice and senior judges. He can also commute deathsentences and issue reprieves without explanation.   The decree, which el-Bashir signed as head of the ruling15-officer junta, named him ``supreme constitutional authority inthe country.''   Shortly after Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi's civiliangovernment was overthrown in a bloodless coup on June 30, el-Bashirmade himself prime minister, minister of defense and militarycommander-in-chief of this East African nation.   He dissolved Sudan's 36 political parties and banned allnewspapers and magazines.   In the past, Sudan's chief justice was elected by other judges.Senior judges were nominated by the chief justice and appointed bya five-member State Council.   El-Bashir has accused officials of the former government andmany political party members of corruption. He has said thoseaccused of wrongdoing will stand trial. El-Mahdi has beenimprisoned with about 40 former senior political figures.</TEXT></DOC>